"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Fritz, Gerhard, Erwin, Heinz, Otto, Reinhold, Siegfried, Wilhelm.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>guot</i> ‘good’ or ‘capable’, German and Yiddish <i>gut</i>. This may be a nickname, but in the Middle Ages the term also denoted a freeman or a vassal of noble birth, and the surname may be a status name from this sense. As a Jewish surname it is often artificial. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, and Czechia. Compare   Gut   and   Good  .","History: This is the name of a (Swiss) German Mennonite family, among the Mennonites in the US established mainly in the Americanized form   Good  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gut","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Franciszek, Irena, Jozef, Krystian, Krystyna, Ludwik, Wojciech.  German Erwin, Hans, Hertha, Urs.  Jewish Moshe, Shai.","Swiss German, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Guth  . Compare   Gutmann  .","Polish: of German origin (see   Guth  , compare 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bonus","meanings":["German: humanistic surname, a translation into Latin of   Guth   or   Gut   ‘good’, from Latin <i>bonus</i>.","Polish; Czech (<b>Bonuš</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bonifacy</i>, Czech <i>Bonifác</i> (see   Boniface  )."]},{"name":"Guthmiller","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Reinhold, Milbert, Otto.","Americanized form of German <b>Guthmüller</b>, a nickname or distinguishing name from Middle High German <i>guot</i> ‘good’ (see   Guth  ) + <i>mūler</i> ‘miller’."]}]},{"name":"Valentin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Danish vernacular form of Latin <i>Valentinus</i>.  See  <b>Valentine</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1670184,"age":23,"year":"1598","julianDay